===Verb===
{{en-verb|accommodat}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|often|reflexive}} To render fit, suitable, or correspondent; to adapt.
#: {{syn|en|adapt|conform|adjust|arrange|suit}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''accommodate''' ourselves to circumstances}}
#* '''1712''' June 18, {{w|Joseph Addison}} and {{w|Richard Steele}}, ''[[w:The Spectator (1711)|The Spectator]]'', number 475, collected in ''The Spectator'', volume VII<sup>[https://books.google.com/books?id=n7VKAAAAcAAJ]</sup>, London: J. and R. Tonson and S. Draper, published 1753, page 15:
#*: IT is an old Obſervation, which has been made of Politicians who would rather ingratiate themſelves with their Sovereign, than promote his real Service, that they '''accommodate''' their Counſels to his Inclinations, and adviſe him to ſuch Actions only as his Heart is naturally ſet upon.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause to come to [[agreement]]; to bring about [[harmony]]; to [[reconcile]].
#: {{syn|en|reconcile}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''accommodate''' differences}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To provide [[housing]] for.
#: {{ux|en|to '''accommodate''' an old friend for a week}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To provide with something desired, needed, or convenient.
#: {{ux|en|to '''accommodate''' a friend with a loan}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To do a favor or service for; to [[oblige]].
#: {{syn|en|oblige}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To show the [[correspondence]] of; to apply or make suit by analogy; to adapt or fit, as teachings to accidental circumstances, statements to facts, etc.
#: {{ux|en|to '''accommodate''' prophecy to events}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give consideration to; to allow for.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To contain comfortably; to have space for.
#: {{ux|en|This venue '''accommodates''' three hundred people.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|rare}} To adapt oneself; to be conformable or adapted; become adjusted.

